            <title><![CDATA[Our Most Anticipated Games Of The Year, Another Assassin's Creed Shadows Delay, And More Of The Week's Top Stories]]></title>
            <link>https://kotaku.com/switch-2-leaks-assassins-creed-shadows-delay-1851737102</link>
            <guid>https://www.resetera.com/threads/our-most-anticipated-games-of-the-year-another-assassins-creed-shadows-delay-and-more-of-the-weeks-top-stories.1079847/</guid>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[https://kotaku.com/switch-2-leaks-assassins-creed-shadows-delay-1851737102<br/><br/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div><div><figure id="" data-id="c73d5e0018940f5fd553263f63ba282f" data-recommend-id="image://c73d5e0018940f5fd553263f63ba282f" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="in-house-art" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Nintendo / Lego / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Rockstar Games / Kojima Productions / Dot Emu / Ubisoft / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Ubisoft<!-- -->, <!-- -->Acer / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Remedy / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Photo<!-- -->: <!-- -->Nintendo<!-- -->, <!-- -->Nintendo</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="c73d5e0018940f5fd553263f63ba282f" data-recommend-id="image://c73d5e0018940f5fd553263f63ba282f" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>This week, we took the opportunity to look ahead to what 2025 has in store, and reminded ourselves (and you!) of the many, many exciting games coming our way in the next 12 months. Also, the steady drumbeat of Switch 2 leaks seems to be speeding up, <em>Assassin’s Creed Shadows </em>has been hit with another delay, and at CES, Acer revealed a very large gaming “handheld.” All this and more awaits in the pages ahead.</p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="4fffca9298740f84c1347148b2e7f59a" data-recommend-id="image://4fffca9298740f84c1347148b2e7f59a" data-format="png" data-width="1600" data-height="899" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Astro Bot and friends turn off their PS5. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Astro Bot and friends turn off their PS5. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="4fffca9298740f84c1347148b2e7f59a" data-recommend-id="image://4fffca9298740f84c1347148b2e7f59a" data-format="png" data-width="1600" data-height="899" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Astro Bot and friends turn off their PS5. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p><span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/psa-turn-off-your-ps5-faster-by-scrolling-left-not-ri-1845669127&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/psa-turn-off-your-ps5-faster-by-scrolling-left-not-ri-1845669127">I only ever turn my PlayStation 5 off a few times a year</a></span>, and it’s usually when there’s an unexpected power outage or I accidentally hit the red switch on the power strip it’s plugged into. My PS5 yells at me when I turn it back on and I vow never to do it again. Apparently only about 50 percent of players live this way, however. - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/ps5-unplug-turn-off-welcome-hub-sony-design-resume-1851733029&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/ps5-unplug-turn-off-welcome-hub-sony-design-resume-1851733029">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="3738ed7730edddefa962011195beb639" data-recommend-id="image://3738ed7730edddefa962011195beb639" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Art shows the biggest games coming in 2025. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Art shows the biggest games coming in 2025. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Rockstar Games / Kojima Productions / Dot Emu / Ubisoft / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="3738ed7730edddefa962011195beb639" data-recommend-id="image://3738ed7730edddefa962011195beb639" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Art shows the biggest games coming in 2025. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>After a quieter year for bigger releases in 2024 (<span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/best-video-games-2024-pc-ps5-xbox-switch-1851291118?_gl=1*1s6bmsv*_ga*MzQzNjkwNDM2LjE2NDY2NjQ1NzQ.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNjI2MDk0MS4yNDcuMS4xNzM2MjcwNjE0LjYwLjAuMA..&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/best-video-games-2024-pc-ps5-xbox-switch-1851291118?_gl=1*1s6bmsv*_ga*MzQzNjkwNDM2LjE2NDY2NjQ1NzQ.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNjI2MDk0MS4yNDcuMS4xNzM2MjcwNjE0LjYwLjAuMA..">though there was still plenty of great stuff overall</a></span>), 2025 has the potential to blow the lid off things with a ton of blockbusters ranging from the unexpectedly delayed <em>Assassin’s Creed Shadows</em> to the long-awaited <em>Grand Theft Auto VI </em>(<span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/gta-6-development-2026-delay-rockstar-office-release-1851359831&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/gta-6-development-2026-delay-rockstar-office-release-1851359831">which could also still get delayed—boo, hiss</a></span>). A ton of major games still don’t have specific release dates, and some of the biggest potential releases—a new 3D <em>Mario </em>from Nintendo, for example— haven’t even been officially announced yet. For now though, and working with the ever-shifting video game release calendar as it’s currently constituted, here are <em>Kotaku</em>’s most anticipated upcoming games of 2025.   - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/big-games-coming-out-2025-gta-6-borderlands-4-1851730256&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/big-games-coming-out-2025-gta-6-borderlands-4-1851730256">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="0758f7e3d376d1a62f1578a1039361e5" data-recommend-id="image://0758f7e3d376d1a62f1578a1039361e5" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A Switch OLED being put into its dock." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A Switch OLED being put into its dock." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Photo<!-- -->: <!-- -->Nintendo</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="0758f7e3d376d1a62f1578a1039361e5" data-recommend-id="image://0758f7e3d376d1a62f1578a1039361e5" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A Switch OLED being put into its dock." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Nintendo’s <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-announcement-ai-4k-motherboard-leak-1851731108&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-announcement-ai-4k-motherboard-leak-1851731108">ongoing refusal to announce the Switch 2</a></span> has reached the point of being downright absurd. As <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-leaks-reveal-release-date-reddit-1851725408&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-leaks-reveal-release-date-reddit-1851725408">leaks continue apace</a></span>, we’re piecing together the unacknowledged console like a jigsaw puzzle, rapidly leaving Nintendo with nothing else to say but, “Yup, that.” The latest pieces come from third-party manufacturers; some via a GameStop employee leaking new SKUs listed on the store’s systems, and others from third-party peripheral company Genki. - John Walker <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="d338ef732fb8a6dff33b895698e593d5" data-recommend-id="image://d338ef732fb8a6dff33b895698e593d5" data-format="png" data-width="986" data-height="554" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Lego and Game Boy logos appear next to each other. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Lego and Game Boy logos appear next to each other. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Nintendo / Lego / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="d338ef732fb8a6dff33b895698e593d5" data-recommend-id="image://d338ef732fb8a6dff33b895698e593d5" data-format="png" data-width="986" data-height="554" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Lego and Game Boy logos appear next to each other. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Nintendo just announced a new console and <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925?_gl=1*1hyabow*_ga*ODE3ODM5ODIyLjE3MjA0NjY0NTg.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNjQ0ODEwNC43MS4xLjE3MzY0NDk2OTAuNjAuMC4w&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925?_gl=1*1hyabow*_ga*ODE3ODM5ODIyLjE3MjA0NjY0NTg.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNjQ0ODEwNC43MS4xLjE3MzY0NDk2OTAuNjAuMC4w">it’s still not the Switch 2</a></span>. The console maker is teaming up with Lego to release a Game Boy made of plastic bricks. It follows after a previous collaboration in which the two companies released a <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;External link&quot;,&quot;https://click.linksynergy.com/deeplink?id=xzXATABADTI&amp;mid=13923&amp;u1=KT-&amp;murl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lego.com%2Fen-us%2Fproduct%2Fnintendo-entertainment-system-71374&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://click.linksynergy.com/deeplink?id=xzXATABADTI&amp;mid=13923&amp;u1=KT-&amp;murl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lego.com%2Fen-us%2Fproduct%2Fnintendo-entertainment-system-71374" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener noreferrer nofollow noskim" data-vtas-click="self:InlineUrl:inline-url-postbody">Lego NES</a></span> together, complete with retro TV that displayed the first level of the original <em>Super Mario Bros</em>.  - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/lego-game-boy-price-release-date-tetris-nintendo-1851736436&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/lego-game-boy-price-release-date-tetris-nintendo-1851736436">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="347b5d8eb012de4630eed3bfd51444c1" data-recommend-id="image://347b5d8eb012de4630eed3bfd51444c1" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A blonde lady appears to be delighted by her Switch OLED model." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A blonde lady appears to be delighted by her Switch OLED model." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Photo<!-- -->: <!-- -->Nintendo</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="347b5d8eb012de4630eed3bfd51444c1" data-recommend-id="image://347b5d8eb012de4630eed3bfd51444c1" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A blonde lady appears to be delighted by her Switch OLED model." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Articles <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/switch-2-dock-joy-cons-rumors-leaks-ces-2025-1851735925">saying Switch 2 leaks and rumors are appearing like a torrent</a></span> are appearing like a torrent, as CES 2025 produced a new round of speculation, hope, confusion and possible visions of the unrevealed device. All the while, Nintendo has sat silently, presumably watching our frenetic rushing about with arch amusement, perhaps taking some sort of pleasure in not actually announcing the console. But last night, the Japanese company finally spoke up, only to tell us all to sit back down. - John Walker <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-rumors-genki-ces-2025-official-1851736830&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-rumors-genki-ces-2025-official-1851736830">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="3218488f8ef37002a81163ae498adeb8" data-recommend-id="image://3218488f8ef37002a81163ae498adeb8" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Two images show grown adults holding the massive Acer Nitro 11. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Two images show grown adults holding the massive Acer Nitro 11. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Acer / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="3218488f8ef37002a81163ae498adeb8" data-recommend-id="image://3218488f8ef37002a81163ae498adeb8" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Two images show grown adults holding the massive Acer Nitro 11. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Computer maker Acer is one of the few PC tech companies that hasn’t released a <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/valve-steam-deck-pc-console-switch-horizon-zero-dawn-re-1848628507&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/valve-steam-deck-pc-console-switch-horizon-zero-dawn-re-1848628507">Steam Deck-like handheld gaming device</a></span>. That changes later this year when it releases not one but three different portable PC devices, one of which is so big that it almost looks like a joke and really begs the question if it’s even a handheld device anymore. - Zack Zwiezen <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/astro-nitro-blaze-11-steam-deck-ces-2025-size-handheld-1851734392&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/astro-nitro-blaze-11-steam-deck-ces-2025-size-handheld-1851734392">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="b659cf1597d15ff0e2049816710d7e13" data-recommend-id="image://b659cf1597d15ff0e2049816710d7e13" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="b659cf1597d15ff0e2049816710d7e13" data-recommend-id="image://b659cf1597d15ff0e2049816710d7e13" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Sony has debuted some wild-looking, <em>Star-Trek</em>-holodeck-like technology that, if it works as advertised, will let people step into the world of <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/last-of-us-2-tlou-remastered-review-1851167660&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/last-of-us-2-tlou-remastered-review-1851167660"><em>The Last of Us</em></a></span><em> </em>and get up close and personal with the franchise’s grotesque spore zombies. This new tech will even let you uh...smell them.  - Zack Zwiezen <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/new-sony-tech-holodeck-last-of-us-ces-2025-smell-vr-ps5-1851734687&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/new-sony-tech-holodeck-last-of-us-ces-2025-smell-vr-ps5-1851734687">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="c00c0f69c36bb3d58146a55288c98310" data-recommend-id="image://c00c0f69c36bb3d58146a55288c98310" data-format="png" data-width="1015" data-height="565" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A PlayStation logo appears on a black DualSense controller. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A PlayStation logo appears on a black DualSense controller. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Sony / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="c00c0f69c36bb3d58146a55288c98310" data-recommend-id="image://c00c0f69c36bb3d58146a55288c98310" data-format="png" data-width="1015" data-height="565" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A PlayStation logo appears on a black DualSense controller. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>The PlayStation 5 lineup of consoles and accessories continues to expand. Just a couple of months after the 30th Anniversary set was released, Sony has revealed another lineup of color variants, this time in all-black. The new PlayStation Portal looks especially slick.  - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/ps5-black-portal-cover-plates-dualsense-edge-pulse-1851733979&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/ps5-black-portal-cover-plates-dualsense-edge-pulse-1851733979">Read More</a></span></p></div></div></div>]]></content:encoded>
